Short glimpses of language features worth exploring. TO ADD MORE.


Validate or destructure a computed value without wrapping it in a function. Soft gates return _—or advance inside {?}—while strict gates stop and throw:
answer := {?
  ReadPrimary() ?- value: [value ? :Integer] ?!- value: [value &gt; 0];
  ReadBackup() ?- {: value, status }: [status == :ready];
  0
}
The first gate also chooses how errors from the candidate expression itself are handled. Each candidate runs once, successful arms return that original value, and all trial bindings stay local.



RiX can store an exact complex number as Cayley(r, t), where r is its nonnegative exact magnitude and t = tan(theta/2) is a stereographic direction coordinate. This avoids transcendental angles while making multiplication, division, integer powers, reciprocal, and conjugation algebraic:
z := .Complex.Cayley(1 + 1~{i});
z                              ## Cayley(sqrt2, sqrt2 - 1)
(z^3).Cartesian()              ## -2 + 2i
The negative real direction uses one projective Infinity point. Addition and subtraction take an exact Cartesian bridge and return to Cayley form. See Exact Cayley Polar Complex Numbers.

